# VD KeyValue Store
A REST-API version controlled key-value store.

## Technologies

This project uses: 
* node
* express
* mongoose

Testing Frameworks/DevTools:
* mocha
* chai
* chai-http
* nodemon
* postman (not listed in `package.json`)

Dependencies:
* mongodb (serving on `http://127.0.0.1:27017`)


## Setup
To run this project, download and install via:
```
$ git clone https://github.com/gabrielwu84/vd-keyvalue-store.git
$ cd vd-keyvalue-store
$ npm install
```

**Note**: for the commands in the following sections to work, please ensure that an instance of _[mongodb](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/administration/install-community/)_ is running locally (at `127.0.0.1`) and serves port `27017`. Also, running this program would overwrite any database named *`object`* on the instance. 

### Launch Server

*Execute:* `$ npm start `

*Expected Output:*

```
Listening on port 3000
```

### Run Test Cases

*Execute:* `$ npm test`

*Expected Output:*

```
Objects
/POST /object
  ✓ it should POST a key-value object and return the object with a timestamp
/GET /object/mykey
  ✓ it should GET value of object by given key
/POST /object
  ✓ it should POST update the key with the new value and return the object with current timestamp
/GET /object/mykey
  ✓ it should GET the new value of the key
/GET with timestamp of first POST
  ✓ it should return the value of the first object
/GET with timestamp before first POST
  ✓ it should return 'key not found'
/GET an unknown key
  ✓ it should return 'key not found'
```

## Features/Usage
**Note**: there is currently an instance of this program hosted at http://gabrielwu84.ddns.net:3000/. All examples listed here can be tested at that address. 

1. Create/Update key via `/POST` request on  `/object` with the content `{"mykey"; "value1"}` placed in the body. 
   *Example `/POST` request made in [postman](https://www.postman.com/)* - 
   <img src="resources/images/fig1-1_post_eg.png" title="Fig 1.1 - POST Example">

2. Retrieve current value of a key via a `/GET` request on`/object/mykey` ([open example in browser](http://gabrielwu84.ddns.net:3000/object/mykey)).

3. Retrieve a previous value of the key by specifying the `timestamp` parameter along with the `/GET` request, e.g. `/object/mykey?timestamp=1621249614225` ([open example in browser](http://gabrielwu84.ddns.net:3000/object/mykey?timestamp=1621249614225)).
